Critical: 4 scanners PARALLEL. Correlator + prioritizer SEQUENTIAL.
Deep-dive loop iterates only for critical/high. Loop has hard cap 2x.
Report-builder always runs last.Build a complete Multi-Agent System called "code-reviewer" at
/tmp/code-reviewer. Do NOT just plan it — actually create the files,
run live tests, and report results.

ARCHITECTURE: Parallel fan-out then aggregator (4 agents)

  code input
      |
      v
  review-orchestrator
      |
      +-- parallel start -----------------------+
      |                                         |
      +-> style-reviewer     (lint, formatting) |
      |                                         |
      +-> security-reviewer  (vulns, secrets)   |
      |                                         |
      +-> perf-reviewer      (perf, complexity) |
      |                                         |
      +-> test-reviewer      (coverage, edge)   |
      |                                         |
      parallel end (all 4 results) --------------+
      |
      v
  review-aggregator   (merges + prioritizes)
      |
      v
  final review report


STEP 1 — Initialize the project skeleton
Run: python3 ~/.config/goose/recipes/tools/dev_generic_init.py
     --init /tmp/code-reviewer --components all

STEP 2 — Create 4 parallel agents + 1 aggregator in
         /tmp/code-reviewer/recipe/sub/:

1. style-reviewer.yaml
   - Reviews code for: lint errors, formatting, naming conventions,
     import order, dead code
   - Returns: {issues: [{file, line, severity, message, suggestion}]}

2. security-reviewer.yaml (MANDATORY — security gate)
   - Reviews code for: hardcoded secrets, SQL injection, XSS,
     insecure dependencies, missing auth checks
   - Returns: {issues: [{file, line, severity, cwe_id, fix}]}
   - This is a hard quality gate. Any HIGH severity issue
     blocks the merge.

3. perf-reviewer.yaml
   - Reviews code for: O(n^2) loops, blocking I/O, memory leaks,
     redundant computation, missing caching
   - Returns: {issues: [{file, line, severity, impact_ms, fix}]}

4. test-reviewer.yaml
   - Reviews code for: missing tests, edge cases, mock coverage,
     flaky patterns
   - Returns: {issues: [{file, line, severity, missing_scenarios}]}

5. review-aggregator.yaml
   - Receives {style_issues, security_issues, perf_issues, test_issues}
   - Merges into a single prioritized list (critical, high, medium, low)
   - Calculates overall score (0-100)
   - Decides: approve | request_changes | needs_discussion
   - Returns: {score, decision, summary, all_issues_sorted}

STEP 3 — Create orchestrator root recipe
/tmp/code-reviewer/recipe/code-reviewer.yaml that runs the 4 reviewers
in PARALLEL (no dependencies between them) and then dispatches to
review-aggregator. Document the parallel execution in instructions.

STEP 4 — DASHBOARD SETUP (mandatory)
a) Set up MCP dashboard for the new project:
   - cd /tmp/code-reviewer
   - mkdir -p .mas/mcp
   - Copy MCP server files from mas-engineer:
     cp /tmp/mas-engineer/mas-engineer/.mas/mcp/server.js .mas/mcp/
     cp /tmp/mas-engineer/mas-engineer/.mas/mcp/package.json .mas/mcp/
     cp /tmp/mas-engineer/mas-engineer/.mas/mcp/dashboard.html .mas/mcp/
     cp /tmp/mas-engineer/mas-engineer/.mas/mcp/mas-dispatch-monitor.html
        .mas/mcp/
   - Run: cd .mas/mcp && npm install
   - Register code-reviewer-dashboard extension in
     ~/.config/goose/config.yaml (under extensions:)
b) First dashboard-data refresh:
   - python3 ~/.config/goose/recipes/tools/dev_dashboard_data.py
     /tmp/code-reviewer
c) Verify dashboard:
   - cat /tmp/code-reviewer/.mas/dashboards/data.json | python3 -m json.tool
     (must have: version, timestamp, workspace, mode, project_name,
      agents, changes, improvement, dispatch, build, health,
      health_trend)
   - Check that "agents.total" = 5 and "agents.healthy" = 5
   - Check that "project_name" = "code-reviewer"
   - Check that "workspace" = "/tmp/code-reviewer"

STEP 5 — LIVE TEST (mandatory):
a) goose run --recipe /tmp/code-reviewer/recipe/code-reviewer.yaml
   --no-session --explain
b) goose run --recipe /tmp/code-reviewer/recipe/sub/style-reviewer.yaml
   --no-session --explain
c) goose run --recipe /tmp/code-reviewer/recipe/sub/security-reviewer.yaml
   --no-session --explain
d) goose run --recipe /tmp/code-reviewer/recipe/sub/perf-reviewer.yaml
   --no-session --explain
e) goose run --recipe /tmp/code-reviewer/recipe/sub/test-reviewer.yaml
   --no-session --explain
f) goose run --recipe /tmp/code-reviewer/recipe/sub/review-aggregator.yaml
   --no-session --explain
g) python3 -c "import yaml; [yaml.safe_load(open(f))
   for f in ['/tmp/code-reviewer/recipe/code-reviewer.yaml',
            '/tmp/code-reviewer/recipe/sub/style-reviewer.yaml',
            '/tmp/code-reviewer/recipe/sub/security-reviewer.yaml',
            '/tmp/code-reviewer/recipe/sub/perf-reviewer.yaml',
            '/tmp/code-reviewer/recipe/sub/test-reviewer.yaml',
            '/tmp/code-reviewer/recipe/sub/review-aggregator.yaml']]"
h) Test MCP server starts: timeout 5 node /tmp/code-reviewer/.mas/mcp/
   server.js
   (should print "Framework Dashboard MCP Server running" on stderr
    before timeout)

STEP 6 — Report:
- List all 6 yaml files created with line counts.
- Show dashboard data.json summary (12 keys, 5 agents).
- Show MCP server files installed.
- Show extension registration in config.yaml.
- Show PASS/FAIL for 6+6+5+4 = 21 checks.
- Show any YAML errors with line numbers.

